posts.title: Book/movie/show recommendations for elementary kids. Looking to teach them proper, conservative history in a fun way
posts.content:
Homeschool family of 6. My oldest is in 2nd grade. We use the Ron Paul Curriculum, and I'm happy with it.

However, I'm finding there isn't a strong element of history in the social studies courses at the younger grades. It's more civics, geography, national monuments, inventors etc. I was a little surprised at this, but I believe social studies shifts to history in 4th grade in that curriculum, at which point they work their way forward from antiquity to the modern day.

Anyway there is a gap there, and I don't really want to wait for it to be presented in school. Foundations can be laid now, which they are. As an example, I asked my 7 year old if she knew what the story of Thanksgiving was and she couldn't really tell me. So I talk to my kids about stuff, but I'm hoping I can surround them with books that will make them proud to be American, and more than that understand what it even is to be American.

I posed this question to another forum, and I got some interesting suggestions. I thought I would share them here, and see if anyone can suggest more:

*Tuttle Twins by Connor Boyack

*Rush Revere by Rush Limbaugh

*Little Patriots (website/cartoon series/worksheets) by Ben Carson

*The Complete Life and Times of Scrooge McDuck

*Little House book series by Wilder

I have the original run of the Tuttle Twins books, and they're good, but they are more focused on abstract ideas and principles, and less about history. I want my kids to be able to discuss the founders with some appreciation of what they were trying to do and why. I would like them to understand the revolutionary war, especially with respect to liberty (as opposed to the modern treatment given in public schools).

Any suggestions?
